04661nam a22008655i 9783110523089DE-B159720190723020930.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190723s2016    gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831105230897 a10.1515/97831105230892doi  a(DE-B1597)474005  a(OCoLC)979627181  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLIT0110002bisacsh04a4202231 aKempf, Elisabeth, eauthor.10aPerforming Manuscript Culture :bPoetry, Materiality, and Authorship in Thomas Hoccleve's "Regement of Princes" /cElisabeth Kempf. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2016] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (216 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTrends in Medieval Philology ;v33  aDissertationcFU Berlind2014.00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- t1. Introduction: the Regement of Princes as a Manuscript Fiction -- t2 "Hoccleve, fadir myn, men clepen me": Textual Biography in the Regement of Princes -- t3. "That text I undirstonde thus alwey": Glosinge in the Regement of Princes -- t4. "Of his persone, I have heere his liknesse Do make": Mediality and Conceptions of Authorship in the Regement of Princes -- t5. Conclusions -- tWorks Cited -- tImages -- tIndices0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis study conceives of Thomas Hoccleve's Regement of Princes (1410-1413) as an essentially performative text, one that expresses its awareness of the manuscript culture in which it is so firmly rooted. The openness of manuscripts is a recurring subject in the Regement and is not only expressed through mere descriptions of, but through complex references to this manuscript context. Performances of manuscript culture manifest themselves in several aspects of the text. The first is the narrator persona, and especially the question of how persona and text are intertwined. The second is the constantly recurring interpretation of "es from authoritative sources that pervades the Regement. This urge to interpret is expressed both in the tradition of adding marginal glosses and in the process of subjecting the text to an exegetical reading. The third aspect is the relation between text and images in the Regement's manuscripts, which shows how mediality is performed and how the manuscript context is made the focus of this performance. In this monograph, all of these aspects are studied in a mindset that combines the concept of performativity with the postulations of Material Philology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2019) 4aHoccleve, Thomas. 4aMaterial Philology. 4aPerformativity. 4aPerformativität. 4aRegement of Princes. 4aThomas Hoccleve. 70(DE-601)1046232840(DE-588)4130545-0aAutorschaft2gnd 70(DE-601)1052323430(DE-588)4192723-0aFiktion2gnd 70(DE-601)2483937740(DE-588)4512697-5aMaterialität2gnd 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2016z9783110485264oZDB-23-DKU0 cEPUBz97831105225870 cprintz978311052245740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110523089423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110523089.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aZDB-23-DGGb2016  aZDB-23-DKUb2016